title: Iran executes three men connected to anti-government protests
description: Rights groups say they were accused unfairly, made to confess under duress and convicted without sufficient evidence, to deter dissent.

title: Border crossings down, but many migrants released to U.S. to ease crowding
description: About 11,000 recent border crossers were deported in the past week. But 21,000 were released to await a U.S. court date, which may spur others to try to cross.

title: Four children are missing after a plane crash in Colombia. Here’s what we know.
description: Colombia's president said that the four siblings had been found, but later retracted his tweet and apologized. Their fate remains uncertain.

title: These are the Western air defense systems protecting Ukraine
description: These systems have proved essential to Ukraine as Russia bombards critical infrastructure and civilian targets.

title: Zelensky, on surprise Saudi visit, seeks Arab League support in war
description: Zelensky used his address to build common cause with countries that have experienced their own years of violent strife, and to plead for stronger condemnation of Russian President Vladimir Putin’s aggression.

title: Ukrainians, crossing Dnieper River, test Russian lines on southern front
description: As Ukraine prepares a major counterattack to seize back occupied territory, some soldiers are training to launch offensive actions across the war’s most formidable frontline.

title: Helmut Berger, Austrian actor and muse to Visconti, dies at 78
description: He was perhaps best known for starring in a pair of historical dramas, “The Damned” and “Ludwig,” directed by his partner Luchino Visconti.

title: China sends a subtle message to Central Asia: Rely on us, not Russia
description: Beijing and Moscow are allies against the West but that doesn't mean they aren't rivals on their borders, as Xi Jinping showed when hosting a China-Central Asia Summit.

title: After dissolving legislature, Ecuador’s president says he’s leaving, too
description: Guillermo Lasso, who sent the National Assembly home, triggering new elections within six months, told The Washington Post that he has no plan to run in them — and doesn’t care who replaces him.

title: The Smiths bassist Andy Rourke dies aged 59
description: Andy Rourke, bassist for British alt-rock legends the Smiths, died after a lengthy illness with pancreatic cancer, his representatives and guitarist Johnny Marr said.

title: Police officer Tasers 95-year-old woman, sparking outcry and inquiry
description: The woman, who has dementia, was in critical condition with a head injury. Australian police said she approached officers — slowly, using a walker — with a steak knife.

title: Ukraine live briefing: U.S. won’t block Europe’s F-16 exports for Kyiv; Zelensky expected at G-7 summit
description: President Biden is at the Group of Seven summit, where the war is a top agenda item and where Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky is set to appear in person.

title: Arab embrace of Assad underscores divergence with U.S. over Syria
description: Officials in Washington insist that U.S. sanctions on Syria will remain, and that a regional rapprochement isn’t a sign of waning influence in the Middle East.

title: Away from the G-7, non-Western powers seek peace in Ukraine
description: While the United States and other Western countries vowed to arm Ukraine to the hilt, countries elsewhere pushed for a cessation in hostilities and a negotiated peace.

title: Ukraine’s President Zelensky to attend G-7 summit in Japan in person
description: The Russian invasion of Ukraine is one of the top items on the agenda at this weekend's summit, where leaders on Friday announced new sanctions on Moscow.
